                                      muKern v.1.0.062026

A minimal microkernel design for x86_64, ARMv8-A and RV64, 
plus a working proof-of-concept that boots on all three
and drops you into a tiny serial REPL.

INSTALL

1. Build the container.

    $ podman build -t osdev -f Containerfile .

2. Build and run kernel.

QEMU's serial is wired to your terminal.
Quit QEMU with: Ctrl-A then x

    $ podman run --rm -it -v "$PWD":/build:Z osdev sh

    Verify toolchain

    > aarch64-linux-gnu-gcc --version
    > riscv64-linux-gnu-gcc --version
    > qemu-system-x86_64 --version
    > make all # or make ARCH=$(ARCH) build 
    
    Build based on $(ARCH) (ex. riscv64, x86_64, arm64).
    The `:Z` suffix relabels the mount for SELinux hosts;
    drop it if your host does not use SELinux.

    Quitting QEMU
    
    All `run-*` targets use `-nographic`, which
    multiplexes the QEMU monitor onto your terminal.
    To exit: press Ctrl-A, release, then x. (Inside the 
    REPL you can also type `halt` to park the CPU, then *
    Ctrl-A x to close QEMU.)

NOTES

- No KVM needed. TCG emulation is intentional for 
  portability; it is slower but works in any rootless 
  container.
- `-v "$PWD":/work:Z` - the `Z` is for SELinux relabeling.
  On Debian/Ubuntu hosts without SELinux it is harmless;
  on some setups you may prefer `:z` (shared) if multiple
  containers touch the tree.
- Apple Silicon / non-x86 hosts. The x86_64 target needs
  host gcc to emit x86_64 code; on a non-x86 host, build 
  the x86_64 kernel with an `x86_64-linux-gnu` cross
  compiler instead and add it to the image. The arm64 and 
  riscv64 targets are unaffected (they already cross-compile).
